		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV><FONT color=#cccccc>
<P>I have been playing Everquest for a year now. Having reached level 57, I am noticing the rifts between my Mage and other classes. I have read through many of these postings and the postings on </FONT><FONT color=#3333ff>http://www.magecompendium.com/</FONT><FONT color=#cccccc> trying to come up with some simple solutions for these problems, and I may have some ideas worth hearing.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>I think the thing we all struggle with the most is defining the Mage class in Everquest: Mages can conjure elemental allies to aid them in combat. Mages can cast moderate to powerful direct damage spells from the Magic and Fire domains, as well as some mediocre DOT spells. Mages can summon some equipment/tools/ammo/foci of varying potency. Mages can conjure some useful pet items that enhance many casters summoned pets. Mages can buff them selves with Regenerative spells, Elemental resistance spells, and Armor spells. Mages can buff them selves and others with fire based damage shields. Mages can buff their pets with Haste, Str, Clarity, shrinking, and Movement spells. Mages can heal their pets. Mages have dominion over summoned creatures (Attack Spells, Mez Spells, Charm Spells). Mages can cannibalize their pets for mana (Reclaim, Draw..etc.). Mages can debuff enemies by removing their buffs or lowering their resistance to attacks. Mages can summon (i.e. not conjure) their pet or other adventurers to their side. Mages also have some utility spells like Invisibility, Identify, Eye Zoom/Tallon (kinda related to conjuring pets), and Gate.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>All in all, Mages are a pretty flexible and varied in their talents, which makes defining the Mage class (and ultimately fixing the class) difficult. I think we can all agree that the greatest strength of the Mage profession are the Elemental pets that aid the Mage. </P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>PETS - Unfortunately these allies are loosing the "arms race" with the other mobs in Everquest. Other mobs in EQ have tons more hit points and do considerably more damage than the Mage’s pet. However, it should never be our intention to make our pets equal in power to the other mobs in EQ. Just as most fighters should never be expected to solo a mob by him self without support, we mages should not have the expectation that our pet could take a mob single handedly. So the trick is to have a pet that can do decent amounts of damage scalar with the challenges offered by upcoming expansions, have enough hitpoint to deal with the newer harder hitting mobs coming out. After all, we use our pets as DPS machines, Meat Shields, Mana Batteries, Ghetto Crowd Control, Tanks, Off Tanks, Sacrificial Lamb…etc. Unfortunately this really cannot be addressed with a new pet buff or a new Earth Pet. Pet focuses help, but Pet focuses can only go so far towards bringing the Mage pets inline with the ever growing challenges and dangers ahead, and Sony cannot be expected to come out with spell after spell in order address the ever evolving meat grinder that we all know an love as Everquest!</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>Wanna solve the pet problem….? Simple, make the pets scale up to the threats out there. How do you do that? </FONT><FONT color=#ccff00>GIVE THE PETS ALL OF THE ABILITY ENHANCEMENTS AND BENEFITS FROM THE MAGE’S EQUIPMENT AND BUFFS</FONT><FONT color=#cccccc>. Right now pets get their master’s saves, why not everything else (including haste, regen, flowing thought, attack, and especially defence). There is always going to be bigger better gear out there, and there is always going to be more powerful buffs as more and more expansions come out. As the mage grows in power, so does his pet, and it won’t require some hideously complex algorithm to achieve this goal. If the mage is elementally equipped, then his pet will be as well. I think it would be fascinating for a mage to have to balance his own spell caster needs in equipment and buffs versus the attribute enhancements he could make for his ally.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>Pets also have a DPS issue. And while that issue would be slightly mitigated by the above solution, other steps should be made in order to flesh out the mage’s ability to dish out sustained damage. I think this exists in the form of the rarely used </FONT><FONT color=#ccff00>Rage of Zoom spell</FONT><FONT color=#cccccc>. I think the Rage of Zoom spell should be changed and the summoned pet should be akin to the mobs like those in the Host of Elements AA. A Pet that argos your current target and beats on it until it or the target dies and then poof its gone. Give the Rage pet a near immunity to spells and AOE attacks. Keep the hit points low so beating it with a stick will send it away. You would need to remove the knock back from the Rage pet, and may want to include a timer or low level DOT that takes it out of play before the recast time for the spell is reached. Finally you create three more rage spells, for the rest of the elements (Tempest of Xegony, Crashing Wave or Marr, Conflagration of Ro…etc). By doing this, you would give the group mage a little extra punch that he can use every few minutes (useable every few fights due to a fairly high re-cast time), and the Raid Mage’s DPS would increase considerably due to the potential of having ALL FOUR pets in play on a really tough mob. The tougher the boss, the longer the fight, the more pets the mage can sick on the boss during the raid. See it is scalar!!</P>
<P>Also, turning the Deafening Decoy Pet into a similar kind of spell would probably be a welcome enchancement, thant and making the casting time instantaneous.</P>
<P>Oh, one more thing, PLEASE don’t make the Fire Pet into just another fighter. There are just some circumstances where you need a ranged attack solution, and the Fire Pet is that. Not that I am saying the Fire Pet is ok as he is right now, his spell selection needs to be tweaked and his role should be more of a fire support/DD machine. Loose Roots, Snares, and the AOE spells, keep the rest.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>DAMAGE SPELLS&nbsp; - I feel that the resist values for our DD spells should be increased, or our MALO spells enhanced in order to deal with these tougher higher resist mobs coming out of the ole Everquest Mob Works. This is definitely a issue that Mages are loosing ground in. As tougher more dangerous mobs are being developed, our spells are becoming less effective. Frankly,</FONT><FONT color=#ccff00> I think resists modifiers should be based partially on the caster’s attributes.</FONT><FONT color=#cccccc> Again, going with scaling theme, if you base the resist modifiers wholly or partly on the caster’s attributes, the caster will be able to deal with tougher mobs as he gains access to more powerful stat affecting equipment. Otherwise, I feel the Mage damage spells are fine.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>PET GEAR&nbsp;- Bigger better pet gear is always welcome, but wouldn’t be necessary if the Pet benefited from the Mage’s equipment bonuses. However, I feel that the Pet’s gear and bonuses inferred from the Mage’s buffs/gear should stack. If someone takes the time to summon some gear and slap it on their pet, I think it is only fair that the two should stack. Also, it was suggested that there be summoned gear ONLY for mage pets. I think this is a bad idea; the coding for setting up a new kind of flag for mage pets would require a lot of work. But more importantly, we are Mages, you know Dominion over summoned creatures, and we should cherish and celebrate out role a "Pet Buffers" and not horde it for our selves. If a beast lord’s pet becomes more powerful than my pet because it has some really nice pet gear, well damnit it should...it was "buffed" by a mage after all!!</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>MAGE SELF BUFFS - The mage self buffs are for the most part fine. Although, I would be hesitant to move those into the realm of targeted or group buffs. Other casters can do buffs like that, and they can do it a lot better. The precedence has been set that these kind of spells in the Mage’s spell book are Self buff only, and I think they should be left there. It’s a flavor/role playing thing.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>PET BUFFS - If Sony tries to create more and more Pet only buff spells to close the gap cause by these more challenging expansions that are coming out, they are just going to end up burning a bunch of development time on a moving target that can’t be hit. As it is, the Burn out line of spells are a scalar solution; Burnout multiplies the power of the pet, not adding an arbitrary number of hit points or defense. So I feel the Pet Buff lines are fine as they are. However, I still strongly suggest that all of the pets stats (HP, Attk, Str, Dex, etc..) are increased by the same amount as the Mage’s. So as the Mage becomes more powerful and becomes Ornately equip, so does his pet. If you think about this, it makes sense, a group is not going to take fighter into the Plane of Time with sub standard gear, a Mage should not expect his pet to make the journey either without the proper outfitting.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>PET HEALS - It is kind of funny, but as a pair the Mage and pet are like a miniature group. The Pet is the tank, the mage is the healer, buffer and nuker. The pet fill his role pretty well, as does the Mage, but with one exception; Mages are lousy pet healers! If a cleric/fighter team set out to conquer the villainy of Norrath with Mage quality spells they would both surely die a quick messy death. Mages should be able to heal their pets with near Cleric efficiency, after all who else will? The Cleric is too busy healing the Fighter. As it stands right now, most mages will rely on chain summoning to tackle tough foes. Healing is too mana inefficient compared to reclaiming and summoning a new pet. This is a sad state of affairs. </FONT><FONT color=#ccff00>The rift between chain summoning and healing is much too wide.</FONT><FONT color=#cccccc> That gap needs to be closed and healing needs to be a viable alternative to "Jobber, show me how the monster works."</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>PET CANNI&nbsp; - Pet canni is fine as it is. However, I would include a version of the spell that also increased the Magician’s health regeneration rate.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>CONJURE ALLY AND HERO -&nbsp; These spell lines are class defining roles for the Mage. A Mage just isn’t a mage without Call of the Hero. Enhancing these spells is a worthwhile endeavor. Variations that call the group, Summon a fallen ally’s body, and summons heros across zone lines are all awesome ideas. These abilities would make mages a lot more "group/raid friendly" and would help to further define the roles of Magicians.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>DOMINION OVER SUMMONED CREATURES - Spells that affect summoned creatures are a touchy subject for many of us. I have always felt that these kinds of spells were a class defining features of the Magician. Mages are masters of Elemental, Conjuration, and Summoning magic… ergo masters of beings created or summoned using those kinds of magic. I am happy with the spells as they are right now (Although I would lower the mana costs on many of the attack spells). While summoned mobs are rare, and these spells would be used infrequently, I feel these spells were a quintessential part of the Mage profession. Mages should have a specialty or a niche role to play on Norrath, and there should be a couple places where a Mage can go and OWN THAT ZONE!! I for one would like to see Sony expand on these summoned only lines of spells. I would also like to see a few more zones where summoned mobs roam. But again summoned creatures should be uncommon and special…just like Mages.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>I know this posting was long, but I hope the point of view of a relatively new player might be constructive in fleshing out the Mage class. The Magician class isn’t a total lost cause, there are signs of a truly fantastic profession just under the ice. We just need to help Sony thaw it out. </P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>Any comments?&nbsp;&nbsp; -&nbsp; 3…2…1… FLAME ON!! <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0></P></FONT>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
